---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import GeneratorShell from '../../components/GeneratorShell.astro';
import { TWIN_NAMES, TWIN_STYLES } from '../../lib/baby-names';

const title = 'Twin Names Generator | Genfy';
const description = 'Name combinations for twins: two boys, two girls, or one of each. 30+ ideas in English and Spanish, free.';
const stylesEN = TWIN_STYLES.en;

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Should twin names rhyme?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Child psychologists advise against it. Sara/Lara or Liam/Liem make twins get treated as a unit, not as individuals. Better: names that pair aesthetically but stay distinct.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Same syllable count or not?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Ideally yes. Liam and Noah (1+2) flows better than Liam and Bartholomew (1+4).' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Same initials or different?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Different. Same initials complicate paperwork, labels and mail for life. Some parents do it anyway — think 20 years out.' } },
  ],
};
---
<Layout title={title} description={description} lang="en" withSidebar={true} schema={faqSchema}>
  <GeneratorShell lang="en" tag="Babies" title="Twin Names Generator"
    intro="Balanced combinations for twins: two boys, two girls, or one of each. Click and get 12 ideas in seconds.">

    <div slot="tool" class="cn">
      <label for="cn-style">Combination</label>
      <select id="cn-style">
        {Object.entries(stylesEN).map(([k, v]) => <option value={k}>{v}</option>)}
      </select>
      <button id="cn-gen" class="btn btn-primary" type="button" style="margin-top:1rem">Generate 12 combinations</button>
      <div id="cn-out" class="cn-out"></div>
    </div>

    <div slot="content">
      <h2>How to name twins</h2>
      <p>
        Naming twins is one of the most interesting parental challenges: two identities you have to
        think about in parallel, without one cannibalizing the other. Child psychologists agree on
        a basic premise: the names should pair aesthetically, but the kids must be treatable as
        individuals.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Pair without rhyming.</strong> Liam + Noah works. Liam + Liem doesn't — the kids end up as "the twins" forever.</li>
        <li><strong>Same aesthetic energy.</strong> If you pick a classic for one (Sarah), the other should be from the same family (Hannah, Anna, Ruth). Don't mix Sarah with Brooklyn.</li>
        <li><strong>Different initials.</strong> A lifetime of labels, forms and backpacks awaits. Same-letter pairs (M and M) complicate everything.</li>
        <li><strong>Similar syllable count.</strong> 2-3 syllables on both keeps phonetic balance.</li>
        <li><strong>Plan separate nicknames.</strong> If both end up as "Matt", everyone gets confused.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Strategies by gender</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Two boys</strong> (Liam + Noah, Oliver + Henry, Theodore + Asher): balanced classics or balanced moderns — keep the same era.</li>
        <li><strong>Two girls</strong> (Olivia + Emma, Charlotte + Amelia, Hazel + Eleanor): watch endings — don't double up on "-ia" in both.</li>
        <li><strong>Boy and girl</strong> (Liam + Olivia, Noah + Emma): most common pairing. More freedom, but balance still matters.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Common pitfalls</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Rhymes.</strong> Sarah/Lara, Liam/Liem, Olivia/Liva. Cute at birth, complicated in adulthood.</li>
        <li><strong>Same initials.</strong> Every label, certificate and email gets confused.</li>
        <li><strong>One bright, one common.</strong> Pairing Mateo with Cosmo: Cosmo will feel his name is a costume next to his sibling's.</li>
        <li><strong>Cultural register clash.</strong> Sarah + Hudson clashes; Sarah + Hannah flows.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Trends in twin names</h2>
      <p>
        US Social Security Administration data on multiple births shows consistent patterns: parents
        tend to pick pairs of biblical names from the same testament, similar but not identical
        endings, and the same syllable count. Liam + Noah, Olivia + Emma, Henry + Oliver are top
        combos every year.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div slot="faq">
      <details><summary>Should twin names rhyme?</summary><p>No. Better: pair aesthetically but stay distinct.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Same syllable count?</summary><p>Ideally yes. Phonetic balance.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Same initials?</summary><p>Different. Saves a lifetime of paperwork confusion.</p></details>
    </div>
  </GeneratorShell>
</Layout>

<style>
  .cn-out { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: 0.5rem; margin-top: 1.25rem; }
  .cn-item { padding: 0.625rem; background: var(--bg-soft); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); font-weight: 600; text-align: center; cursor: pointer; transition: border-color 0.1s; }
  .cn-item:hover { border-color: var(--primary); }
</style>

<script define:vars={{ DATA: TWIN_NAMES }}>
  const styleEl = document.getElementById('cn-style');
  const out = document.getElementById('cn-out');
  const gen = document.getElementById('cn-gen');

  function pick(arr) { const i = new Uint32Array(1); crypto.getRandomValues(i); return arr[i[0] % arr.length]; }

  function generate() {
    const s = styleEl.value;
    const pool = DATA[s].en;
    const set = new Set();
    let attempts = 0;
    while (set.size < Math.min(12, pool.length) && attempts < 300) { attempts++; const pair = pick(pool); set.add(pair[0] + ' & ' + pair[1]); }
    out.innerHTML = '';
    [...set].forEach(n => {
      const el = document.createElement('div');
      el.className = 'cn-item';
      el.textContent = n;
      el.title = 'Click to copy';
      el.addEventListener('click', () => { navigator.clipboard.writeText(n); el.textContent = '✓ ' + n; setTimeout(() => el.textContent = n, 900); });
      out.appendChild(el);
    });
  }
  gen.addEventListener('click', generate);
  generate();
</script>
